docs.abstract: The Young America’s Foundation, a well-funded group based in Washington, is on a mission to “restore sanity” at schools by deploying provocative speakers.
docs.snippet: The Young America’s Foundation, a well-funded group based in Washington, is on a mission to “restore sanity” at schools by deploying provocative speakers.
docs.lead_paragraph: BUFFALO — “Let’s give it up for the racists that are hosting this event!” someone yelled, and the crowd roared, foot-stomping in unison, then breaking into song: Woody Guthrie’s “This Land Is Your Land.” One member of the audience held up a sign, “Queers Against Islamaphobia.” Another unfurled a banner: “Muslims Welcome. Fascists Get Out.”

headline.main: The Conservative Force Behind Speeches Roiling College Campuses
headline.print_headline: Fiery Speeches on Campuses,  Backed by a Conservative Force

docs.abstract: A grass-roots organization is seeking to protect tribal lands and gain equal ownership rights in a country where, by law, women inherit less than men.
docs.snippet: A grass-roots organization is seeking to protect tribal lands and gain equal ownership rights in a country where, by law, women inherit less than men.
docs.lead_paragraph: OULAD SEBATA, Morocco — For most of her life, Saida Soukat’s days were filled with the routines of the farm, working the fields and minding the cattle. A recent Tuesday found her doing something far different, though, speaking before a group of women during their biweekly protests to demand a halt in the state-sanctioned privatization of traditional tribal collectives, called the Sulaliyyate lands.

headline.main: In a Fight for Land, a Women’s Movement Shakes Morocco
headline.print_headline: In a Fight for Land, a Women’s Movement Shakes Morocco

docs.abstract: The Milwaukee County sheriff, who spoke at the Republican convention, once said ISIS and Black Lives Matter activists were allying to destroy America.
docs.snippet: The Milwaukee County sheriff, who spoke at the Republican convention, once said ISIS and Black Lives Matter activists were allying to destroy America.
docs.lead_paragraph: David A. Clarke, the Milwaukee County sheriff who once claimed that ISIS and Black Lives Matter activists were forming an alliance to destroy America, said on a radio show Wednesday that he would accept a senior position at the Homeland Security Department.

headline.main: Polarizing Sheriff David Clarke Says He’ll Take a Top Homeland Security Job
headline.print_headline: Polarizing Wisconsin Sheriff  Says He’s Taken Federal Job

docs.abstract: The monument has emerged from obscurity in the last few weeks, as four prominent memorials to the Confederacy in New Orleans were pulled down amid protests.
docs.snippet: The monument has emerged from obscurity in the last few weeks, as four prominent memorials to the Confederacy in New Orleans were pulled down amid protests.
docs.lead_paragraph: ST. LOUIS — The angry, divisive fight over public symbols of the Confederacy has swept through Columbia, S.C., Birmingham, Ala., and New Orleans. This week, the debate made its way some 600 miles north, up the Mississippi River, to St. Louis, the home of a Confederate memorial many residents did not know was in their midst.

headline.main: Few in St. Louis Knew Confederate Memorial Existed. Now, Many Want It Gone.
headline.print_headline: In Popular Park, a Point of Contention

docs.abstract: President Nicolás Maduro’s government is harshly repressing protest, but Venezuelans are no longer afraid.
docs.snippet: President Nicolás Maduro’s government is harshly repressing protest, but Venezuelans are no longer afraid.
docs.lead_paragraph: CARACAS, Venezuela — This episode took place on my street in downtown Caracas last week. People were shouting, running past my building, trying to escape from a contingent of national guardsmen who had opened fire a block away with buckshot, rubber bullets and tear gas canisters on a peaceful demonstration outside the offices of PDVSA, the state-owned oil company.

docs.abstract: Officials at the civil rights group said its cutting of ties with Cornell William Brooks after only three years was part of a “systemwide refresh.”
docs.snippet: Officials at the civil rights group said its cutting of ties with Cornell William Brooks after only three years was part of a “systemwide refresh.”
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The national board of the N.A.A.C.P. voted Friday to dismiss the organization’s president, Cornell William Brooks, after only three years, pledging a “systemwide refresh” at the nation’s largest and most storied civil rights group in order to confront President Trump more vigorously.

headline.main: N.A.A.C.P., Energized by Liberal Activists, Dismisses Its President
headline.print_headline: N.A.A.C.P., Energized by Liberal Activists, Dismisses Its President
